{"id":"1901.03469","submitter":"Jaehyun Hong","authors":"Jaehyun Hong and Sui-Chung Ng","title":"Local holomorphic mappings respecting homogeneous subspaces on rational\n  homogeneous spaces","comments":"28 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG math.CV","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $G/P$ be a rational homogeneous space (not necessarily irreducible) and\n$x_0\\in G/P$ be the point at which the isotropy group is $P$. The\n$G$-translates of the orbit $Qx_0$ of a parabolic subgroup $Q\\subsetneq G$ such\nthat $P\\cap Q$ is parabolic are called $Q$-cycles. We established an extension\ntheorem for local biholomorphisms on $G/P$ that map local pieces of $Q$-cycles\ninto $Q$-cycles. We showed that such maps extend to global biholomorphisms of\n$G/P$ if $G/P$ is $Q$-cycle-connected, or equivalently, if there does not exist\na non-trivial parabolic subgroup containing $P$ and $Q$. Then we applied this\nto the study of local biholomorphisms preserving the real group orbits on $G/P$\nand showed that such a map extend to a global biholomorphism if the real group\norbit admits a non-trivial holomorphic cover by the $Q$-cycles. The non-closed\nboundary orbits of a bounded symmetric domain embedded in its compact dual are\nexamples of such real group orbits. Finally, using the results of Mok-Zhang on\nSchubert rigidity, we also established a Cartan-Fubini type extension theorem\npertaining to $Q$-cycles, saying that if a local biholomorphism preserves the\nvariety of tangent spaces of $Q$-cycles, then it extends to a global\nbiholomorphism when the $Q$-cycles are positive dimensional and $G/P$ is of\nPicard number 1. This generalizes a well-known theorem of Hwang-Mok on minimal\nrational curves.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 11 Jan 2019 03:41:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-01-14"}
